before_text:
\section{Taxonomy}
Our taxonomy plays a crucial role in our research by offering a well-structured framework to address the complexities of our problem statement. At its core, the taxonomy is rooted in the overarching category of "Stress," which is the foundation for our classification system. From this foundation, the taxonomy branches into distinct dimensions, including "physical," "psychological," "psychosocial," and "psychospiritual." These dimensions, in turn, yield a rich array of subcategories and intricately detailed leaves, each offering a nuanced perspective.
\bigbreak

To establish a comprehensive taxonomy of stress categories, this study incorporated insights from reputable sources, including an in-depth exploration of stress types and symptoms.The taxonomy development process was informed by a comprehensive review of literature, including analyses and classifications from MentalHelp.net (MentalHelp.net, n.d.). This resource played a crucial role in providing a nuanced understanding of various stress categories and enriching the depth of our study. By leveraging this external reference, we aimed to ensure a robust representation of stress categories

This hierarchical taxonomy is not merely an organizational tool; it serves as a profound lens through which we examine the collected data. It empowers us to systematically categorize and interpret the data with precision and depth, ensuring that every facet of the problem statement is thoroughly explored. Each subcategory is further thoroughly described with an example for the ease of annotating the data. It enables us to uncover subtle connections, identify patterns, and derive meaningful insights, ultimately strengthening the robustness of our findings. Table [1] displays the taxonomy, and the detailed taxonomy, including the examples, can be found in the appendix.

% \begin{figure*}
% % \includegraphics[width=18cm]
% % {latex/Figures/Taxonomy_main.pdf}
% \includegraphics[trim={cm 0cm 0cm 20 cm},clip,width=1\textwidth]{latex/Figures/Taxonomy_main.pdf}
% \caption{Taxonomy}
% \label{tab:taxonomy}
% \end{figure*}

\subsection{Aligning Taxonomy with Existing Labels}

The Dreaddit dataset \citet{turcan-mckeown-2019-dreaddit}, as a valuable resource, already contains a set of labels that have been used to categorize the data. Our goal in this alignment process is to bridge the gap between these existing labels and our taxonomy, creating a harmonious and comprehensive framework for analysis. By mapping the pre-existing labels to the corresponding categories and dimensions in our taxonomy, we aim to establish a strong link that enables us to interpret and categorize the data with precision and depth and helps us to annotate the rest of the data with much clarity. This alignment not only enhances the efficiency of our analysis but also ensures that our findings are built upon a foundation of existing knowledge and insights, ultimately contributing to a more nuanced and insightful exploration of the dataset. Table[2] illustrates the linkages between the labels extracted from the Dreaddit dataset and the constructed taxonomy.

