\subsection{Curated Data Compilation}

The work relies mainly on three distinct datasets, each providing valuable insights into the research statement. \\

\begin{itemize}
    \item Dreaddit\footnote{We downloaded the dataset from \url{http://www.cs.columbia.edu/~eturcan/data/dreaddit.zip}.}, sourced from \citet{turcan-mckeown-2019-dreaddit}, is a comprehensive collection comprising 2837 training and 715 testing records. It encompasses a diverse array of input features, including social media texts, associated labels representing mental health issues, confidence scores, and various other related metrics including word categories from the Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count (LIWC) and Yule’s I measure. The anticipated outcomes span a range of mental health conditions, such as relationships, anxiety, PTSD, assistance, homelessness, almost homelessness, domestic violence, survivors of abuse, stress, and food pantry.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item The pair dataset\ by \citet{min2022pair} focuses on the brief interactions between the counselors and the clients, offering insights into various levels of reflective listening skills. It consists of 318 records and includes client statements, typically presented to counseling trainees paired with counseling responses that exemplify different levels of reflective quality, spanning low quality, medium quality, and high quality.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item 
Counsel data by \citet{bertagnolli2020counsel} revolves around councelchat.com, an exemplary expert community platform aimed at assisting counselors in building their professional reputation and fostering meaningful connections with potential clients. This dataset comprises 568 records and revolves around therapists' responses to client inquiries, with users having the option to 'like' responses they find most valuable.
\end{itemize}
