% % \includegraphics[width=18cm]
% % {latex/Figures/Taxonomy_main.pdf}
% \includegraphics[trim={cm 0cm 0cm 20 cm},clip,width=1\textwidth]{latex/Figures/Taxonomy_main.pdf}
% \caption{Taxonomy}
% \label{tab:taxonomy}
% \end{figure*}
\begin{figure*}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[trim={0cm 11cm 0cm 3cm},width=160mm]{latex/Figures/Stress_taxonomy.pdf}
\caption{Taxonomy}
\label{tab:scores_report}
\end{figure*}
\bigbreak


\subsection{Aligning Taxonomy with Existing Labels}

The Dreaddit dataset, as a valuable resource, already contains a set of labels that have been used to categorize the data. Our goal in this alignment process is to bridge the gap between these existing labels and our taxonomy, creating a harmonious and comprehensive framework for analysis. By mapping the pre-existing labels to the corresponding categories and dimensions in our taxonomy, we aim to establish a strong link that enables us to interpret and categorize the data with precision and depth and helps us to annotate the rest of the data with much clarity. This alignment not only enhances the efficiency of our analysis but also ensures that our findings are built upon a foundation of existing knowledge and insights, ultimately contributing to a more nuanced and insightful exploration of the dataset. Table[1] illustrates the linkages between the labels extracted from the Dreaddit dataset and the constructed taxonomy.

