\section{Taxonomy}
Our classification system plays a crucial role in our research by offering a well-structured framework to address the complexities of our problem statement. At its core, the taxonomy is rooted in the overarching category of "Stress," which is the foundation for our classification system. From this foundation, the taxonomy branches into distinct dimensions, including "physical," "psychological," "psychosocial," and "psychospiritual." These dimensions, in turn, yield a rich array of subcategories and intricately detailed leaves, each offering a nuanced perspective.
\bigbreak
This hierarchical taxonomy is not merely an organizational tool; it serves as a profound lens through which we examine the collected data. It empowers us to systematically categorize and interpret the data with precision and depth, ensuring that every facet of the problem statement is thoroughly explored. Each subcategory is further thoroughly described with an example for the ease of annotating the data. It enables us to uncover subtle connections, identify patterns, and derive meaningful insights, ultimately strengthening the robustness of our findings. Figure [1] displays the taxonomy, and the detailed taxonomy, including the examples, can be found in the appendix.

