The sentences in the datasets not only capture an individual's experience of stress at a specific point in time but also encompass reflections on past stressors or concerns about potential future stress. The table [3] illustrates instances of texts from the aggregated dataset indicating the stress encountered in the past, present, and anticipated in the future. Overall, the dataset comprises diverse textual entries, each accompanied by essential metadata, including the text content, assigned category and subcategory labels, text length, and the percentage of both positive and negative sentiment, allowing for a nuanced exploration of stress-related expressions.

\begin{table*}
{\setlength{\tabcolsep}{14.5pt}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{p{2.5cm}p{12cm}}
\hline
\textbf{Time Frame} & \textbf{Example Sentence} \\
\hline
\hline
Past & In a desperate need to share my burden and seek solace, I recall the time when I was involved in a devastating car accident. The traumatic incident resulted in a tangled fracture in my right leg, immobilizing me. Confined to the bed, I was surrounded by endless hours of torment and pain. However, I made the conscious choice to rise from this adversity, using it as an opportunity to enhance my drawing skills for my future design career. Juggling the intense pain, the drowsiness from the medication, and my will to improve was a battle, but my persistence won. Today, I stand not only as a skilled artist but also as a testament to resilience. \\
\hline
Present & Everything about my existence was a burden to her. I wasn't exposed to one huge trauma. I was little traumas over a long period of time. I now feel very unsafe all the time and scared. I'm constantly afraid of I don't know what. \\
\hline
Future & At the same time, I’ve been going crazy because if I’m not thinking about something else, I’m thinking about him and various kink-related acts. This isn’t anything I’ve actually experienced before (hell, I still don’t get attraction), so I’m confused. My issue is, he’s going back overseas for uni in a couple of days, and we’ll be seeing each other (in our larger group) tomorrow. Should I bring something up? Should I just leave it? \\
\hline
