\subsection{Selected Data Source and Rationale}

After carefully considering multiple data source options, we ultimately opted for a data utilization strategy involving the second type of data source described in Section 2, where the data consists of texts provided by the speaker and is subsequently annotated by third-party individuals. This approach is a pragmatic choice, given that we are annotating data from three distinct datasets we have meticulously collected. Using third-party annotators helps mitigate individual bias and subjectivity in the labeling process. Furthermore, this method allows for a more rigorous and collaborative review of the data, ensuring that the labels generated are accurate and reflect the underlying context. The data obtained through this strategy will play a pivotal role in our research, as it forms the foundation for our comprehensive taxonomy, which will be elaborated upon in subsequent sections.\\

\subsection{Curated Data Compilation}

The work relies mainly on three distinct datasets, each providing valuable insights into the research statement. \\

\begin{itemize}
    \item Dreaddit\footnote{We downloaded the dataset from \url{http://www.cs.columbia.edu/~eturcan/data/dreaddit.zip}.}, sourced from \citet{turcan-mckeown-2019-dreaddit}, is a comprehensive collection comprising 2837 training and 715 testing records. It encompasses a diverse array of input features, including social media texts, associated labels representing mental health issues, confidence scores, and various other related metrics including word categories from the Linguistic Inquiry and Word Count (LIWC) and Yule’s I measure. The anticipated outcomes span a range of mental health conditions, such as relationships, anxiety, PTSD, assistance, homelessness, almost homelessness, domestic violence, survivors of abuse, stress, and food pantry.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item The pair dataset\footnote{We downloaded Pair  from \url{https://lit.eecs.umich.edu/downloads.html\#PAIR}.} by \citet{min2022pair} focuses on the brief interactions between the counselors and the clients, offering insights into various levels of reflective listening skills. It consists of 318 records and includes client statements, typically presented to counseling trainees paired with counseling responses that exemplify different levels of reflective quality, spanning low quality, medium quality, and high quality.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item 
Counsel data\footnote{We downloaded Counsel Data from \url{https://github.com/nbertagnolli/counsel-chat}} by \citet{bertagnolli2020counsel} revolves around councelchat.com, an exemplary expert community platform aimed at assisting counselors in building their professional reputation and fostering meaningful connections with potential clients. This dataset comprises 568 records and revolves around therapists' responses to client inquiries, with users having the option to 'like' responses they find most valuable.
\end{itemize}
\bigbreak
To see the distinctive features of each dataset, see Table \ref{tab:dataset_comparison}. Our primary focus revolves around the rich textual content extracted from these datasets, strategically complemented by pertinent tags and labels. This curated summary aims not only to illuminate the core elements of the datasets but also to provide a holistic perspective for a more nuanced exploration of the data landscape. To achieve a comprehensive and well-distributed representation of various data categories, we supplemented the aggregated dataset with syntactic data. This additional dataset, comprising approximately 49.03\% of the complete data, contributes significantly to a more nuanced understanding of different stress categories. The remaining 50.97\% of the aggregated data is strategically divided, encompassing 31.65\% Dreaddit data, 25.32\% Pair data, and 43.04\% Counsel data. This allocation ensures a balanced integration of diverse sources, enriching the dataset with a variety of perspectives.
\bigbreak
