\begin{abstract}
In the era of large language models (LLMs) where the distinction between human-written and machine-generated texts is getting blurry, this paper poses and investigates the question of the existence of discernible, unique linguistic properties within texts crafted by human writers. Positing that these linguistic signatures may lie beyond surface structure, we utilize discourse analysis in linguistics and introduce a novel approach involving hierarchical parse trees and recursive hypergraphs to uncover distinctive discourse patterns in texts generated by LLMs and humans. Empirical findings illustrate that while both LLMs and humans generate distinct discourse patterns influenced by domains, human-written texts tend to structurally vary more depending on the nature of domains. We also find that the addition of hierarchical discourse features improves the detectors' overall performance as well as on out-of-distribution samples and paraphrases samples, highliting the utility of the discourse 




the promise of "discourse motifs" in exploring linguistic signatures, revealing that both LLMs and humans generate distinct discourse patterns influenced by domains. Integration of hierarchical discourse-level features enhances authorship detection, and a unique dataset for longer-form machine-generated content in the creative writing domain is contributed, filling a critical gap in existing research. The study contributes valuable insights into the evolving landscape of machine-generated texts and the quest for robust authorship detection methods.









\end{abstract}

