\begin{abstract}

In the era dominated by large language models (LLMs), where the line between human-crafted and machine-generated texts is increasingly blurred, this paper delves into the inquiry of identifying discernible and unique linguistic properties intrinsic to texts authored by human writers. Recognizing that these linguistic nuances may extend beyond surface structure, we employ discourse analysis grounded in linguistics. Introducing a novel methodology, we leverage hierarchical parse trees and recursive hypergraphs to unveil distinctive discourse patterns in texts produced by both LLMs and humans.
