\section{Modeling Hierarchical Structures in Documents}\label{sec:hierarchical_structures}
\dk{Provide one sentence rationale behind this section; basically you are saying that we need a expressive representation of hierarchical discourse structure for motif analysis}
When crafting texts, authors often use structure in texts to convey meaning systematically, thereby enhancing the clarity, coherence, and persuasiveness of their written work. In linguistics, the examination of document structure falls under discourse frameworks \citep{mann1987rhetorical,miltsakaki-etal-2004-penn,lascarides2007segmented}. This paper adopts Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) \citep{mann1987rhetorical} due to its widespread usage and the availability of openly accessible pretrained parsers.

\subsection{Rhetorical Structure Theory}
RST assumes that any well-written document can be parsed into a (recursive) discourse tree. In this tree, each leaf node, called an elementary discourse unit (EDU), corresponds to a phrase within a sentence, while higher-level nodes integrate these lower-level representations into more complex structures, such as phrases to sentences to paragraphs. It does so by assigning a discourse label (e.g., elaboration, contrast, cause, effect, etc.) to a relation (i.e., edge) between nodes. The linked nodes can be either ``nuclei'' (main ideas) or ``satellites'' (supporting details) depending on their relative importance in the relation. Figure \ref{fig:hypergraph_example} illustrates how a quote from Steve Jobs is segmented into seven EDUs.\footnote{We note that the full RST tree can be found in Fig. \ref{fig:rst_tree_example}.} In this paper, we adopted an existing RST parser from \citet{liu-etal-2021-dmrst} to construct the trees used in our experiments.

\subsection{Conversion to Hypergraphs}

\begin{figure}[!t]
\centering
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/hypergraph_example.pdf}}
\caption{
A quote from Steve Jobs and its RST tree (Fig. \ref{fig:rst_tree_example}) converted into a hypergraph format. A hexagonal node represents the ``nucleus'' node while a circular one denotes the ``satellite'' node. Each node is labeled with a span of EDU indices that it covers. The 8-point star-shaped node is the root node of the graph, encompassing all subgraphs and EDUs.\vspace{-4mm}}
\label{fig:hypergraph_example}
\end{figure}

\dk{Can you highlight the justification of hypergraph conversion more explicitly here? You mentioned it in the middle of the paragraph but better to mention it upfront}
As RST trees naturally exhibit recursion, wherein its discourse relations can encapsulate other relations, and a single relation may span more than two nodes in the case of multi-nuclei relations. We note that this recursive nature aligns with the principles of recursive hypergraphs (or ``Ubergraphs'') in mathematics \citep{Joslyn2017UbergraphsAD}, where a discourse relation corresponds to a \textit{recursive hyperedge}. In short, hypergraphs generalize traditional graphs by allowing edges (or ``hyperedges'') to connect more than two nodes. The recursive hypergraphs further generalize the standard hypergraphs by allowing hyperedges to contain not only nodes but other hyperedges. This leads to a hierarchical structure, where hyperedges at different levels of recursion represent relationships at varying levels of abstraction.

To facilitate ease of analysis, the hypergraph can be transformed into a standard traditional graph form by introducing a dummy edge that (depicted as `hyp.' in Figure \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}), signifying the (expanded) hyperedge relation. From there, we are now able to run standard network analysis algorithms as well as train Graph Attention Networks (GATs) \citep{velickovic2018graph}, leveraging the inherent discourse structure and semantics of documents.

