\section{Proposed Method: Revealing Key Patterns via Discourse Motifs}\label{sec:revealing_key_patterns}
This paper focuses on finding distinctive structural patterns, namely, hierarchical discourse relations based on the RST framework (\S \ref{sec:hierarchical_structures}). Our main investigative approach involves analyzing the distribution of network motifs which are \textit{recurring and statistically significant subgraph patterns} within a larger network. These motifs are often considered as building blocks of larger networks and can provide insights into the organization and dynamics of the system \citep{milo2002networkmotifs}. Specifically, In our study, we apply this methodology to understand how individuals (both humans and machines) craft texts.
\dk{readers might already get lost at this point. Can you remind the steps in Figure 2, and this section discusses how to extract these sub-graphs (or discourse motifs) from the hypergraph?}

\subsection{Network Motifs of Sizes 3, 6, and 9 \dk{Can we use either "discourse motifs" or "network motifs" in the whole paper for consistency? I prefer the former as it sounds more novel and relevant}}
One of the standard ways to construct motifs is to generate all possible non-isomorphic subgraphs of a fixed number of vertices. However, as the number of vertices increases, the number of possible patterns increases super-exponentially, rendering their counting extremely inefficient.
To make matters worse, our RST graphs are \textit{directed} with their edges \textit{labeled} with discourse relations which further increases the complexity.\footnote{We also note that some discourse relations are bidirectional too.}

With this in mind, we start by generating all possible motifs with 3 vertices, a minimal form other than a single edge---this gives us 69 non-isomorphic motifs. To create larger motifs, we pick two size-3 motifs from all possible pairs, join them at all possible nodes, and only keep the non-isomorphic ones, resulting in size-6 motifs. We conduct this process one more round with pairs of size-3 and -6 motifs to produce size-9 motifs.\footnote{As we are joining at motifs their nodes, the total number of nodes for size-6 and -9 motifs can be smaller than 6 and 9, respectively.}
\dk{This part could be more elaborated by adding example motif graphs for sizes of 3 and 6. Showing a couple of example motif images like the artifact paper would be enough. Also, refer to the Figure 12 for full motifs.  }

\begin{table}[!h]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.5\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c|c}
        \toprule
        Size-3 & Size-6 & Size-9 \\
        \midrule
        69 & 592 & 2394\\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Number of non-isomorphic discourse motifs.}
    \label{tab:three_motifs_sizes}
\end{table}


\subsection{Edge-Based Explanations}\label{subsec:network_motifs_founded_on_edge_based_explanations}
When we have a labeled dataset and a trained graph neural networks (GNNs) for the authorship detection task, we can utilize explainability methods like ``GNNExplainer'' \citep{ying2019gnnexplainer} and ``GraphFramEx'' \citep{amara2022graphframex} that elucidate the predictions of GNNs by identifying the nodes or edges whose masking has the most significant impact on the predicted outcome. Since our graphs consist of directed and labeled edges, we require an explanation method tailored to edge-based features for graph attention network (GAT) \citep{velickovic2018graph}. Thus, we employ ``AttentionExplainer'' from GraphFramEx which computes edge masks using the attention coefficients generated by GATs trained on the binary classification task. 
\dk{This section is not clear. From what written here, did you use the edge masks as one of features for your motifs? In my understanding, I thought you just used them for comparison, showing the correlation, instaed of features. If my understanding is correct, I'm not sure here is a good place to discuss about it. }

\subsection{Metrics for Analyses}\label{subsec:metrics}
\dk{Can you draw another conceptual figure to illsutrate this process? Basically, make an expanded version between Step 3 and Step 4 in Figure 2. Showing an illustration of normalization and MF-IDF using the analogy of tokenization and TF-IDF would be helpful. Also, readers might like to know how to use these extracted features as a part of features for detection tasks. So, the final output should be a like a fixed-sized motif vector to be concatenated to text embeddings for detectors. }

Once we gather potentially useful network motifs, we simply count the number of isomorphic subgraphs for each motif across all documents in the datasets. But as the graph isomorphism test is (possibly) NP-intermediate, the process requires heavy engineering feats to maximize computational efficiency such as hashing the subgraphs \citep{ShervashidzeSLMB11} and multiprocessing the datasets.\footnote{The code for experiments will be released for ease of reproducibility.}
\dk{Can we make below more clear? I think considering the whole motif distribution is infeasible, we focus on frequent motifs that appear in the corpus that we use for experiments, similar to constructing a local tokenization scheme for LLM pretraining. Using an anology of token processing in LM would be effective here. (token=motif, text=hypergraph)}
From there, we can identify distinctive motifs by looking at their difference distributions on their normalized counts (\S\ref{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}) as well as computing our proposed ``motif frequency-inverse document frequency (MF-IDF)'' measure (\S\ref{subsubsec:mfidf}).

