\section{Proposed Method: Revealing Key Patterns via Discourse Motifs}\label{sec:revealing_key_patterns}
This paper focuses on finding distinctive structural patterns, namely, hierarchical discourse relations based on the RST framework (\S \ref{sec:hierarchical_structures}). Our main investigative approach involves analyzing the distribution of network motifs which are \textit{recurring and statistically significant subgraph patterns} within a larger network. These motifs are often considered as building blocks of larger networks and can provide insights into the organization and dynamics of the system \citep{milo2002networkmotifs,Takes2018MultiplexNM}. Specifically, we find that when converting a recursive RST tree into a standard graph, it always forms the union of subgraphs with 3 vertices.\footnote{We provide the proof in Appendix \ref{sec:app:unions}.} 

To summarize the approach (Fig. \ref{fig:main_intro_fig}), we gather documents written by humans and LLMs, parse their RST trees, transform them into hypergraphs, and run motif analyses to understand how individuals (both humans and machines) craft texts. The following subsections illustrate how the discourse motifs are systematically formed (\S\ref{subsec:discourse_motifs}) and scored using our proposed metrics (\S\ref{subsec:metrics}).

\subsection{Discourse Motifs of Sizes 3, 6, and 9}\label{subsec:discourse_motifs}
One of the standard ways to construct motifs is to generate all possible non-isomorphic subgraphs of a fixed number of vertices. However, as the number of vertices increases, the number of possible patterns increases super-exponentially, rendering their counting extremely inefficient.
To make matters worse, our RST graphs are \textit{directed} with their edges \textit{labeled} with discourse relations which further increases the complexity.\footnote{We also note that some discourse relations are bidirectional too.}

With this in mind, we start by generating all possible motifs with 3 vertices, a minimal form other than a single edge---this gives us 69 non-isomorphic motifs. To create larger motifs, we pick two size-3 motifs from all possible pairs, join them at all possible nodes, and only keep the non-isomorphic ones, resulting in size-6 motifs. We conduct this process one more round with pairs of size-3 and -6 motifs to produce size-9 motifs.\footnote{As we are joining at motifs their nodes, the total number of nodes for size-6 and -9 motifs can be smaller than 6 and 9, respectively.}
% Depending on how these multiples of size-3 motifs are unioned together, we can form motifs of other sizes 
\dk{This part could be more elaborated by adding example motif graphs for sizes of 3 and 6. Showing a couple of example motif images like the artifact paper would be enough. Also, refer to the Figure 12 for full motifs.  }


\begin{table}[!h]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.5\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c|c}
        \toprule
        Size-3 & Size-6 & Size-9 \\
        \midrule
        69 & 592 & 2394\\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Number of non-isomorphic discourse motifs.}
    \label{tab:three_motifs_sizes}
\end{table}

\subsection{Metrics for Analyses}\label{subsec:metrics}

Once we gather potentially useful network motifs, we simply count the number of isomorphic subgraphs for each motif across all documents in the datasets. But as the graph isomorphism test is (possibly) NP-intermediate, the process requires heavy engineering feats to maximize computational efficiency such as hashing the subgraphs \citep{ShervashidzeSLMB11} and multiprocessing the datasets.\footnote{The code for experiments will be released for ease of reproducibility.}
\dk{Can we make below more clear? I think considering the whole motif distribution is infeasible, we focus on frequent motifs that appear in the corpus that we use for experiments, similar to constructing a local tokenization scheme for LLM pretraining. Using an anology of token processing in LM would be effective here. (token=motif, text=hypergraph)}
From there, we can identify distinctive motifs by looking at their difference distributions on their normalized counts (\S\ref{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}) as well as computing our proposed ``motif frequency-inverse document frequency (MF-IDF)'' measure (\S\ref{subsubsec:mfidf}).

\subsubsection{Motif Difference Distributions}\label{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}
As a simple measure, we consider the difference distribution between the normalized motif distribution of machine-generated texts and that of human-written texts. Each motif count distribution ($\mathcal{M}(g)$) for an RST hypergraph ($g$), is normalized by the size of its graph (i.e., the number of edges, $|E(g)|$) and averaged over a dataset $\mathcal{D}$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}) = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}|} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{D}} \frac{\mathcal{M}(g)}{|E(g)|}
\end{equation}

The difference distribution, $\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}})$, is then:

\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}}) = \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{machine}}) - \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{human}})
\end{equation}

This distribution represents the discrepancies of motifs between the two classes of authorship and can be computed across different domains of texts as well.

\subsubsection{Motif Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (MF-IDF)}\label{subsubsec:mfidf}
Inspired by the term frequency–inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) measure from information retrieval domain, we propose ``motif frequency–inverse document frequency'' (MF-IDF), noting that a motif ($m$) can be considered as a vocabulary of documents that are graphs ($g \in \mathcal{G}$) in our case:

\begin{align*}
    \text{MF-IDF}(m, g, \mathcal{G}) = \text{MF}(m, g) \cdot \text{IDF}(g, \mathcal{G})
\end{align*}

where:
\begin{align*}
    \text{MF}(m, g) = \frac{f_{m, g}}{\sum_{m'\in g}f_{m', g}} \\
    \text{IDF}(g, \mathcal{G}) = \log \frac{1 + |\mathcal{G}|}{1 + |g \in \mathcal{G}: m \in g|} \\

