\subsection{Metrics for Analyses}\label{subsec:metrics}

Once we gather potentially useful discourse motifs, we simply count the number of isomorphic subgraphs for each motif across all documents in the datasets. But as the graph isomorphism test is (possibly) NP-intermediate, the process requires heavy engineering feats to maximize computational efficiency such as hashing the subgraphs \citep{ShervashidzeSLMB11} and multiprocessing the datasets.\footnote{The code afor experiments will be released for ease of reproducibility.}
\dk{Can we make below more clear? I think considering the whole motif distribution is infeasible, we focus on frequent motifs that appear in the corpus that we use for experiments, similar to constructing a local tokenization scheme for LLM pretraining. Using an anology of token processing in LM would be effective here. (token=motif, text=hypergraph)}
From there, we can identify distinctive motifs by looking at their difference distributions on their normalized counts (\S\ref{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}) as well as computing our proposed ``motif frequency-inverse document frequency (MF-IDF)'' measure (\S\ref{subsubsec:mfidf}).

\subsubsection{Motif Difference Distributions}\label{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}
As a simple measure, we consider the difference distribution between the normalized motif distribution of machine-generated texts and that of human-written texts. Each motif count distribution ($\mathcal{M}(g)$) for an RST hypergraph ($g$), is normalized by the size of its graph (i.e., the number of edges, $|E(g)|$) and averaged over a dataset $\mathcal{D}$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}) = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}|} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{D}} \frac{\mathcal{M}(g)}{|E(g)|}
\end{equation}

The difference distribution, $\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}})$, is then:

\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}}) = \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{machine}}) - \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{human}})
\end{equation}

This distribution represents the discrepancies of motifs between the two classes of authorship and can be computed across different domains of texts as well.

\subsubsection{Motif Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (MF-IDF)}\label{subsubsec:mfidf}
Inspired by the term frequency–inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) measure from information retrieval domain, we propose ``motif frequency–inverse document frequency'' (MF-IDF), noting that a motif ($m$) can be considered as a vocabulary of documents that are graphs ($g \in \mathcal{G}$) in our case:

\begin{align*}
    \text{MF-IDF}(m, g, \mathcal{G}) = \text{MF}(m, g) \cdot \text{IDF}(g, \mathcal{G})
\end{align*}

where:
\begin{align*}
    \text{MF}(m, g) = \frac{f_{m, g}}{\sum_{m'\in g}f_{m', g}} \\
    \text{IDF}(g, \mathcal{G}) = \log \frac{1 + |\mathcal{G}|}{1 + |g \in \mathcal{G}: m \in g|} \\
    f_{m, g} = \text{occurences of motif $m$ in graph $g$.}
\end{align*}

