\subsubsection{Motif Difference Distributions}\label{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}
As a simple measure, we consider the difference distribution between the normalized motif distribution of machine-generated texts and that of human-written texts. Each motif count distribution ($\mathcal{M}(g)$) for an RST hypergraph ($g$), is normalized by the size of its graph (i.e., the number of edges, $|E(g)|$) and averaged over a dataset $\mathcal{D}$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}) = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}|} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{D}} \frac{\mathcal{M}(g)}{|E(g)|}
\end{equation}

The difference distribution, $\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}})$, is then:

\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}}) = \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{machine}}) - \mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{human}})
\end{equation}

This distribution represents the discrepancies of motifs between the two classes of authorship and can be computed across different domains of texts as well.

\subsubsection{Motif Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (MF-IDF)}\label{subsubsec:mfidf}
