\subsection{From Local Discourse Motifs to Global Structural Patterns\dk{mention why motif analysis only can provide local patterns, while these global branching stiatistcs or linguistic analysis could further distinguish machine-vs-human text?}}\label{subsec:formality_correlation}
We found the observation (\S\ref{subsubsec:key_motifs}) that human-written texts for more formal and discussional domains, e.g., news summarization (\textsc{XSum}) and ChangeMyView (\textsc{cmv}), seem to contain more ``Joint'' discourse relations where the corresponding child subgraphs are of equal importance (i.e., both are ``nuclei''). While this finding seems to corroborate our main assumption that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts; it is based on the statistics of local discourse motifs albeit computed over the whole graphs. In this section, we try to extend the analysis to include more global features by (1) computing the correlation between the number of hyperedge relations present in graphs and the formality score of the corresponding document (\S\ref{subsubsec:formality_scorer}); and (2) looking at how the overall shape of the document graphs vary across different domains (\S\ref{subsubsec:ra_sc}).

We believe that 


This section investigates if this ``even branching'' would lead to a distinct relationship between one aspect of texts--namely formality--and overall discourse hierarchies.





While this paper looks at the notion of formality of texts in particular, 
\dk{why formality? What's a rationale you believe there is a correlation between branching out effect and formality? Any extension to other styles? What does this correlation study imply for future research?}
To this end, we approach the notion of formality from two different perspectives by (1) looking at the correlation between sentence-level formality scores and occurrences of hyperedges (denoted as ``hyp.'' in Fig. \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}) in all document graphs, and (2) considering the graphs' overall hierarchical structures per domain.

\subsubsection{Formality Scorer}\label{subsubsec:formality_scorer}
We make use of a publicly available sentence-level formality scorer \citep{Babakov2023Formality} that is finetuned on a dataset for formality style transfer task, \textsc{GYAFC} \citep{rao-tetreault-2018-dear}. The model is based on a \textsc{RoBERTa-base} model \citep{liu2019roberta} and computes the score between 0 and 1 range. The formality score is computed for every text generated by humans and machines. Also, for every corresponding document graph, we count the (normalized) frequency of hyperedges for all motifs present in the graph. This is because the hyperedge relations represent higher-level abstractions of text and are thus linked to the discourse hierarchy. 
\dk{Move sentences above to the setup section or appendix.}From there, we compute the Pearson correlation coefficient between the scores and frequencies.

