From Table \ref{tab:overall_f1}, we can see that the addition of motif information to any of the different base encoders consistently improves the classification performance, showing the effectiveness of discourse motifs as auxiliary information to capture the underlying linguistic structure beyond surface lexicons.
\dk{{Particularly, as the model (i.e., GAT) understands the topological struture of discourses, discourse motifs shows signifint improvements (0.67 -> 0.73 on HC3). Also, as the model (i.e., Longformer) has a long-form understanding of large text, discourse motifs further help provide explicit structural difference between ...blah...}}
Even on the paraphrased out-of-domain test set (``OOD-Para'') where the samples are from ``unseen domains'' and ``unseen models'', adding discourse motifs to the detector shows a significant improvement over the baselines.
We posit that this is because discourse-level information is \textit{less dependent} from lexical variations by sentence-level paraphrasing attacks as well as \textit{somewhat universal} across domains.

