\section{Proposed Method: Revealing Key Patterns via Discourse Motifs}\label{sec:revealing_key_patterns}
This paper focuses on finding distinctive structural patterns, namely, hierarchical discourse relations based on the RST framework (\S \ref{sec:hierarchical_structures}). Our main investigative approach involves analyzing the distribution of network motifs which are \textit{recurring and statistically significant subgraph patterns} within a larger network. These motifs are often considered as building blocks of larger networks and can provide insights into the organization and dynamics of the system \citep{milo2002networkmotifs,Takes2018MultiplexNM}. Specifically, we find that when converting a recursive RST tree into a standard graph, it always forms the union of subgraphs with 3 vertices. We highlight the proof in Appendix \ref{sec:app:unions}.

To summarize the approach (Fig. \ref{fig:main_intro_fig}), we gather documents written by humans and LLMs, parse their RST trees, transform them into hypergraphs, and run motif analyses to understand how individuals (both humans and machines) craft texts. The following subsections illustrate how the discourse motifs are systematically formed (\S\ref{subsec:discourse_motifs}) and scored using our proposed metrics (\S\ref{subsec:metrics}).

\subsection{Discourse Motifs as Unions of Triads}\label{subsec:discourse_motifs}
One of the standard ways to construct motifs is to generate all possible non-isomorphic subgraphs of a fixed number of vertices. However, as the number of vertices increases, the number of possible patterns increases super-exponentially, rendering their counting extremely inefficient.
To make matters worse, our RST graphs are \textit{directed} with their edges \textit{labeled} with discourse relations which further increases the complexity.\footnote{We also note that some discourse relations are bidirectional too.}

With this in mind, we start by generating all possible motifs with 3 vertices, i.e., ``triads.'' This is a minimal form of motifs other than a single edge case, ``dyads.'' We select the triads to be the basis motifs be
this gives us 69 non-isomorphic motifs. To create larger motifs, we pick two size-3 motifs from all possible pairs, join them at all possible nodes, and only keep the non-isomorphic ones, resulting in size-6 motifs. We conduct this process one more round with pairs of size-3 and 6 motifs to produce size-9 motifs.\footnote{As we are joining motifs at their nodes, the total number of nodes for size-6 and 9 motifs can be smaller than 6 and 9, respectively.}
We note that depending on how these multiples of size-3 motifs are joined together, we can form motifs of other sizes such as size-4, 5, and 7. Figure \ref{fig:3_6_9_motifs_examples} illustrates examples of size-3, 6, and 9 motifs and Table \ref{tab:three_motifs_sizes} shows the number of identified motifs.

