\section{Experimental Setup}


\subsection{Datasets}\label{subsec:datasets}
Our experiments are conducted on two existing benchmark datasets and one new dataset (\textsc{TenPageStories}) that we created for more in-depth analysis.

\paragraph{\textsc{HC3-English}.} \citet{guo2023close} published the first corpus on human writer vs. ChatGPT comparison. It comprises 24K \textit{paired} responses from human authors and ChatGPT for mostly question-answering (QA) style prompts across 5 domains: Reddit-ELI5, medicine, finance, open QA, and Wikipedia-CS.
% We filter paired responses where the length ratio between two classes of text differs by less than 0.7. 

\paragraph{\textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect}.} \citet{li2023deepfake} proposed \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} dataset which consists of 448K \textit{mostly unpaired} human-written and machine-generated texts from 10 diverse datasets including news article writing, story generation, opinion writing, etc. The machine-generated texts are from 27 mainstream LLMs from 7 sources such as OpenAI and LLaMA. Out of ten domains in the dataset, we focus on the following five considering the diversity and sizes of domains: review writing (\textsc{yelp}), story writing (\textsc{wp}), argument writing (\textsc{cmv}), news summarization (\textsc{xsum}), and writing descriptions for scientific tables (\textsc{sci\_gen}).

\paragraph{\textsc{TenPageStories} (Ours).} It is worth noting that most of the existing datasets on this authorship detection task consist of documents ranging from 200 to 500 tokens, typically a few paragraphs long. This could pose a limitation, particularly in capturing long-term discourse relations effectively. To address this concern, we construct exceptionally lengthy generations based on 20 fictional stories on Project Gutenberg published in early November 2023.\footnote{\url{https://www.gutenberg.org}}

Our generated content is prepared in three distinct settings:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
    \item \textbf{Unconstrained}: We provide the first human-written paragraph of a story and instruct the LLM to iteratively generate continuations of the story.
    \item \textbf{``Fill-in-the-gap''}: We mask $N \in {1, 3, 5}$ paragraphs between a preceding human-written paragraph and a subsequent human-written paragraph. Texts from the previous iterations are taken into account during the generation.
    \item \textbf{Constrained ``fill-in-the-gap''}: Similar to (2), but the masked paragraph(s) now include the first and last sentences of the corresponding human-written paragraph(s), providing more guided contexts.
\end{enumerate}

These settings are designed to enable the observation of long-term discourse patterns while varying the constraints applied to the original contexts. We generate content up to 8K tokens ($\approx$10 A4 pages) in an iterative manner, continuing from the previously generated texts. The unconstrained continuation generates an arbitrary number of tokens per iteration, while the other two scenarios produce paragraphs that are approximately consistent with the corresponding paragraphs in the original text. However, we note that due to the limited input length of the existing discourse parser, we did not use the unconstrained generations in the following analysis (\S\ref{subsec:creative_writing}) and left them for future exploration. The pseudocode for the generation process as well as the prompt templates can be found in Appendix \ref{sec:app:ten_page_stories}.

We acknowledge that different LLMs may demonstrate unique discourse patterns. However, our primary focus is on examining overarching characteristics indicative of machine-generated text, irrespective of the specific model employed. This includes a wide range of machine-generated texts, such as those produced by LLaMA, GPT4, and GPT3.5, among others. We posit that these patterns are foundational features inherent in various types of auto-regressive models, forming the basis of our investigation.

\subsection{Baseline Models}\label{subsec:baseline}
\zae{Mention different settings for baseline models: GNN satelite infos, node embeddings, RF: features only, Longformer, Ignore satelite info text and motifs. Specify variations by notations.}
\dk{Zae, move all details about the baselines, including GNN, RF, Longformer, etc here. Also, move all other technical details regarding experimental steups here instead of the result section. Readers might like to know how to use these extracted features as a part of features for detection tasks. So, the final output should be a like a fixed-sized motif vector to be concatenated to text embeddings for detectors. }
To evaluate the usefulness of discourse motifs, we integrate them into three baseline models: random forests (RF), graph attention network (GAT), and Longformer \citep{beltagy2020longformer}. We illustrate RF is selected 
\dk{Provide a justification of why these models are chosen. Use the models used in prior work as reference. The baseline part is quite weak in my opinion, so provide a good jusitication here.}
Rather than using all of the size-3, 6, and 9 motifs, we selected motifs whose difference in MF-IDF scores is above the mean difference by at least one standard deviation. This resulted in 207 (31 + 96 + 80) selected motifs and we used their normalized counts as additional information (denoted as ``Sel. Motifs'' in Table \ref{tab:overall_f1}) when training GAT and Longformer. Specifically, we concatenate a small vector of 207 dimensions to the mean-pooled representation of GAT and to the \textsc{[CLS]} representation of Longformer, respectively. We describe more details of the experiment in Appendix \S\ref{sec:app:authorship_detection}.

\subsubsection{Edge-Based Explanations}\label{subsubsec:network_motifs_founded_on_edge_based_explanations}
When we have a labeled dataset and a trained graph neural networks (GNNs) for the authorship detection task, we can utilize explainability methods like ``GNNExplainer'' \citep{ying2019gnnexplainer} and ``GraphFramEx'' \citep{amara2022graphframex} that elucidate the predictions of GNNs by identifying the nodes or edges whose masking has the most significant impact on the predicted outcome. Since our graphs consist of directed and labeled edges, we require an explanation method tailored to edge-based features for graph attention network (GAT) \citep{velickovic2018graph}. Thus, we employ ``AttentionExplainer'' from GraphFramEx which computes edge masks using the attention coefficients generated by GATs trained on the binary classification task.

