\subsection{Preliminary Analyses on Discourse Motifs}\label{subsec:motif_analyses}
\dk{Provide high-level questions to answer out of this section first. }
We note that the difference distributions based on MF-IDF scoring are less skewed than using the normalized counts (Fig. \ref{fig:difference_dists_two_ways}) due to the IDF scaling, and thus opt for the measure throughout the experiments.

\subsubsection{Relationship between Motifs and Influential Edges for Explanation}
As a way to evaluate the appropriateness of using network motifs, we explore how they are related to influential edges in Graph Neural Network (GNN) computed by an explanation method.
Note that the influential edges mean edges with high masking values\footnote{The most influential edges whose masking values are larger than $0.99$ are considered in $[0, 1]$.} generated by a graph neural network explainer as described in (\S\ref{sec:exp_setup}).
We then calculate a correlation between frequencies of selected network motifs based on MF-IDF scores and those of influential edges.
To this end, we define two random variables as follows. Let $X$ be the number of single-triads and let $Y$ be the number of influential edges for each graph.
Samples of $X$ and $Y$ are collected from each graph in the datasets (\textsc{HC3-English}, \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect}), and the Pearson correlation coefficient $r_{XY}$ is calculated. 

\begin{figure}[!t]
\centering
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/corr_3_valid_deepfake.png}\vspace{-3mm}
}
\caption{Correlation between selected single-triads with high MF-IDF scores and influential edges computed by a graph neural network explainer on \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} dataset.\vspace{-3mm}}
\label{fig:corr_m3}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[!t]
\centering
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/influential_edge_proportions_valid_deepfake.png}\vspace{-3mm}}
\caption{Proportions of labels of influential edges. Note that ``Non-influential'' means edges whose mask values are under the threshold. Note also that the value ``0.0\%'' in this figure does not indicate the zero, but a very small positive number like ``1e-5\%.''\vspace{-3mm}}
\label{fig:proportion_edge_label_m3}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:corr_m3} shows that frequencies of selected size-3 motifs and influential edges are highly correlated with $r_{XY} \approx 0.99$, indicating that the network motifs may be useful features in determining the authorship of texts. 
\dk{But, then why not simply using GNNs? If discourse motifs are all possible subset relations that can be detected through GNNs, why do we still need discourse motifs? You can mention the explainability aspect and/or lingusitic grounding, etc.}
Figure \ref{fig:proportion_edge_label_m3} shows the proportion of edge labels (i.e., discourse relations) of influential edges. Note that the label ``/'' denotes the dummy hyperedge relation (``hyp.'').


