\subsubsection{Difference Distributions of Motifs across Domains}\label{subsubsec:key_motifs}

\begin{figure}[!ht]
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/motif_m3_mfidf_scores_difference_for_motif_m3.pdf}
  \caption{
Difference in size-3 motif distribution of machine-generated and human-written texts for five different domains in \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} dataset.
  \dk{Can't read the discourse relationship texts. Can you remove the domain name from the figures and move them as sub-captions (or make it legend at the bottom left) to save the horizontal space? Also, make y-axis using e format (e.g., e-3) to save addditional space. 
  For relation annotations, I encourage you to annotate them on Powerpoint and make font size larger. }
  }
  \label{fig:found_motifs}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:found_motifs} shows bar plots for the difference distribution of size-3 motifs across the five domains of texts. Due to space constraints, the plots showcase the top 20 motifs for both machine and human-written texts.
\dk{Any mention of statistical signifance? Without it, nobody will buy this.}
The mean and standard deviation of differences ($\mathcal{M}(\mathcal{D}_{\text{diff}})$) are is 0.00012 and 0.0015, respectively. Notably, machine-generated texts tend to feature more motifs with Background relations, while human-written texts exhibit an inclination towards Temporal discourse relations in domains such as review writing (\textsc{yelp}) and story generation (\textsc{wp}), and contain more Joint relations in domains that demand formality or deeper logical depths (i.e., argument writing (\textsc{cmv}) and news summarization (\textsc{xsum}). We note that Joint discourse relation signifies cases where the corresponding child trees are of equal importance (i.e., ``nuclei'') and thus branched evenly.\footnote{We study this branching effect in Section \ref{subsec:formality_correlation}.}
The texts in table description generation (\textsc{sci\_gen}) are interesting in that the human-written descriptions (taken mostly from academic papers in NLP and machine learning) mainly highlight the changes in performance and this is captured as Temporal, Manner, or Means relations. Table \ref{tab:grounded_examples} shows some grounded examples of texts for prevalent motifs in each domain.\footnote{More examples can be found in Appendix \ref{sec:app:more_grounded_motifs}.}

