\subsection{From Local Discourse Motifs to Global Structural Patterns}\label{subsec:local_to_global}
We found the observation (\S\ref{subsubsec:key_motifs}) that human-written texts for more \textit{formal} and \textit{discussional} domains, e.g., news summarization (\textsc{XSum}) and ChangeMyView (\textsc{cmv}), seem to contain more ``Joint'' discourse relations, wherein the corresponding child subgraphs are of equal importance (i.e., both are ``nuclei''). While this finding seems to corroborate our main assumption that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts; it is based on the statistics of local discourse motifs albeit computed over the whole graphs. In this section, we aim to extend our analysis to include global structures by (1) computing the correlation between the number of hyperedge relations (denoted as ``hyp.'' in Fig. \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}) present in graphs and the formality score of the corresponding document (\S\ref{subsubsec:formality_scorer}); and (2) investigating the overall shape variations of document graphs across different domains (\S\ref{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain}).

\subsubsection{Formality Scores and Hyperedges}\label{subsubsec:formality_scorer}
We make use of a publicly available sentence-level formality scorer \citep{Babakov2023Formality} that is finetuned on a dataset for formality style transfer task, \textsc{GYAFC} \citep{rao-tetreault-2018-dear}. The model is based on a \textsc{RoBERTa-base} model \citep{liu2019roberta} and computes the score between 0 and 1 range. The formality score is computed for every text generated by humans and machines. Also, for every corresponding document graph, we count the (normalized) frequency of hyperedges for all motifs present in the graph. This is because the hyperedge relations represent higher-level abstractions of text and are thus linked to the discourse hierarchy. 
\dk{Move sentences above to the setup section or appendix.}From there, we compute the Pearson correlation coefficient between the scores and frequencies.

\begin{table}[!t]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.75\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c}
        \toprule
        Machine-Generated & Human-Written\\
        \midrule
        $0.08^*$ & $0.39^*$ \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Pearson's $R$ between formality scores and frequency of hyperedges.}
    \label{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}
\end{table}

As shown in Table \ref{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}, the human-written texts over all domains exhibit weak to moderate correlation with the formality style while machine-generated ones seem to show no correlation. 
