before_text:
First, we check how the different generation settings affect the detection performance (Table \ref{tab:overall_f1_ten_page_stories}). As expected the models perform better when longer texts are generated. Also, when the first and last sentences of the human-written texts are additionally provided in the prompt (i.e., ``constrained FIG''), the corresponding generations are easier to detect. We note that the models' f1 scores are low as they produce a lot of false negatives, i.e., predicting actual human-written texts to be machine-generated. However, we can observe that the addition of a small discourse vector significantly improves the performance.


\begin{figure}[!ht]

\begin{subfigure}{\columnwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/plot_motif_diff_FITG_paragraph_m3_motif_m3_hist_norm_by_edges.pdf}
\caption{\textit{Fill-in-the-gap} setting}
\end{subfigure}

\bigskip

\begin{subfigure}{\columnwidth}
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/plot_motif_diff_FITG_FL_m3_motif_m3_hist_norm_by_edges.pdf}
\caption{\textit{Constrained fill-in-the-gap} setting}
\end{subfigure}
\caption{Difference distribution of motifs for \textsc{TenPageStories} under the two \textit{fill-in-the-gap} settings. The x-axis represents unique indices of single-triads while the y-axis shows the difference in MF-IDF scores of machine-generated and human-written texts for each corresponding motif.
\dk{Fonts are too small. Summarize the main finding in caption too, since it's quite difficult to intuitively capture the main message of this figure.
Why not using the same color scheme as Figure 4? Also, why not adding discourse relationship annotations?
}
}
\label{fig:diff_dist_ten_page_stories}
\end{figure}

Similarly, Figure \ref{fig:diff_dist_ten_page_stories} elucidates the distinct motif distributions within \textsc{TenPageStories} across various settings. We can see that the motifs indexed at 0 (Elaboration) and 5 (Joint) seem useful in detecting machine- and human-written texts, respectively. This may imply that human authors tend to construct narratives with a higher prevalence of Joint relations, indicative of more evenly branching structures, in contrast to the patterns found in texts generated by LLMs. Another noteworthy observation is the heightened occurrence of the motif indexed at 28 (Temporal) with increasing text length to generate.



\subsection{From Local Discourse Motifs to Global Structural Patterns}\label{subsec:local_to_global}
We found the observation (\S\ref{subsubsec:key_motifs}) that human-written texts for more \textit{formal} and \textit{discussional} domains, e.g., news summarization (\textsc{XSum}) and ChangeMyView (\textsc{cmv}), seem to contain more ``Joint'' discourse relations, wherein the corresponding child subgraphs are of equal importance (i.e., both are ``nuclei''). While this finding seems to corroborate our main assumption that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts; it is based on the statistics of local discourse motifs albeit computed over the whole graphs. In this section, we aim to extend our analysis to include global structures by (1) computing the correlation between the number of hyperedge relations (denoted as ``hyp.'' in Fig. \ref{fig:hypergraph_example}) present in graphs and the formality score of the corresponding document (\S\ref{subsubsec:formality_scorer}); (2) investigating the overall shape variations of document graphs across different domains (\S\ref{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain})

\subsubsection{Formality Scores and Hyperedges}\label{subsubsec:formality_scorer}

\begin{table}[!t]
    \centering
    \resizebox{0.75\columnwidth}{!}{
    \begin{tabular}{c|c}
        \toprule
        Machine-Generated & Human-Written\\
        \midrule
        $0.08^*$ & $0.39^*$ \\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}}
    \caption{Pearson's $R$ between formality scores and frequency of hyperedges.}
    \label{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}
\end{table}

The formality score is computed for every text generated by humans and machines. Also, for every corresponding document graph, we count the (normalized) frequency of hyperedges for all motifs present in the graph. This is because the hyperedge relations represent higher-level abstractions of text and are thus linked to the discourse hierarchy. 
From there, we compute the Pearson correlation coefficient between the scores and frequencies.

As shown in Table \ref{tab:corr_formality_hyperedge}, the human-written texts over all domains exhibit weak to moderate correlation with the formality style while machine-generated ones seem to show no correlation. This hints that when humans write more structured texts in terms of discourse, the contents are often more formal.

\subsubsection{Branched vs. Chain-Like Structures}\label{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain}
\dk{I guess this shortest path is not relevant to formaltiy?}
Another approach is to differentiate texts by domain and assume that the formality of texts is consistent within the domain. We can then look at the varying levels of graph structures per domain. As illustrated in the Introduction (\S\ref{sec:introduction}), we assume that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts. 

One possible dimension of characterizing this difference in structures is by checking whether the structures are evenly branched or follow a more sequential pattern as illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:branch_vs_chain}.

\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth]{figures/branch_vs_chainlike_structure.pdf}

