\caption{Average shortest path lengths per domain for document graphs. This illustrates that human-authored texts exhibit significant variation across domains, whereas machine-generated texts tend to display less variability. This difference may suggest the existence of ``domain-agnostic writing in machine language,'' representing a potential ``discourse artifact'' for machine-generated texts.
\dk{Increase font sizes for legend and axis texts. Use different bar textures for human and machine. Add error bars.}
\dk{Also, calculate the std or variation across domains, and compare their scores in human and machine explicitly.}
}
\label{fig:shortest_path_len}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:shortest_path_len} depicts the bar plots of ASPL of the two groups over five domains. We can observe that the story generation task (\textsc{WP}) produces texts with the longest ASPL for both groups. While the ASPL for the other four domains is relatively consistent for machine-written texts, human-written texts show another two levels of change in ASPL. Specifically, both news summarization (\textsc{xsum}) and argument writing tasks (\textsc{cmv}) produce ASPL of length 7, followed by review writing (\textsc{yelp}) and table description writing (\textsc{sci\_gen}). This finding shows that human writers are more versatile in arranging linguistic structures of discourse depending on the (nature of) domains.

