\subsubsection{Branched vs. Chain-Like Structures}\label{subsubsec:branch_vs_chain}
Another approach is to differentiate texts by domain and assume that the formality of texts is consistent within the domain. We can then look at the varying levels of graph structures per domain. As illustrated in the Introduction (\S\ref{sec:introduction}), we assume that the linguistic structure of discourse can change depending on factors such as formality, spontaneity, and depth of reasoning in the texts. 

\begin{figure}[ht!]
  \centering
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\columnwidth]{figures/branch_vs_chainlike_structure.pdf}
  \caption{Illustration of document graph structures with different discourse hierarchies. For simplicity, the horizontal edge linking two child nodes is omitted.}
  \label{fig:branch_vs_chain}
\end{figure}

One possible dimension of characterizing this difference in structures is by checking whether the structures are evenly branched or follow a more sequential pattern as illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:branch_vs_chain}.

To quantify this notion, we calculate the average shortest path length (ASPL) of a document graph. For linear or chain-like graphs, the ASPL tends to be relatively short, as nodes are connected in a linear fashion. In contrast, more spread-out graphs will likely have a longer ASPL due to increased distances between nodes. Another closely related metric is the diameter of a graph which is the longest shortest path between any two nodes in the graph. However, as human-written and machine-generated texts are not necessarily paired and could vary a lot in length, we opt for ASPL.

\begin{figure}[!h]
\centering
% <left> <lower> <right> <upper>
{\includegraphics[width=0.95\columnwidth, trim={0cm 0.0cm 0.0cm 0.0cm},clip]{figures/avg_shortest_path_len_per_domain.pdf}}
\caption{Average shortest path lengths per domain for document graphs. This illustrates that human-authored texts exhibit significant variation across domains, whereas machine-generated texts tend to display less variability. This difference may suggest the existence of ``domain-agnostic writing in machine language,'' representing a potential ``discourse artifact'' for machine-generated texts.
\dk{Increase font sizes for legend and axis texts. Use different bar textures for human and machine. Add error bars.}
\dk{Also, calculate the std or variation across domains, and compare their scores in human and machine explicitly.}
}
\label{fig:shortest_path_len}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:shortest_path_len} depicts the bar plots of ASPL of the two groups over five domains. We can observe that the story generation task (\textsc{WP}) produces texts with the longest ASPL for both groups. While the ASPL for the other four domains is relatively consistent for machine-written texts, human-written texts show another two levels of change in ASPL. Specifically, both news summarization (\textsc{xsum}) and argument writing tasks (\textsc{cmv}) produce ASPL of length 7, followed by review writing (\textsc{yelp}) and table description writing (\textsc{sci\_gen}). This finding shows that human writers are more versatile in arranging linguistic structures of discourse depending on the (nature of) domains.

\subsubsection{Upper and Lower Layers of Discourse Graphs for Paraphrased Texts}\label{subsubsec:upper_vs_lower}

\begin{figure}[!ht]
\centering
% <left> <lower> <right> <upper>
{\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth,trim={0cm 0cm 0cm 0cm},clip]{figures/orig_vs_para.pdf}\vspace{-3mm}}
\caption{We posit that sentence-level paraphrasing typically leads to greater variability in lower segments of discourse structures compared to higher segments near the root node.\vspace{-3mm}}
\label{fig:orig_vs_para}
\end{figure}

In this experiment, we look at the discourse structures of original and paraphrased documents regardless of their authorship. We aim to validate our hypothesis that sentence-level paraphrasing induces greater variability in the lower segments of discourse graphs, as these segments correspond to the individual EDUs and their aggregation into sentences. Given the assumption that the overall higher-level discourse structure remains relatively intact, we anticipate that the upper segments will display less structural variability (c.f. Figure \ref{fig:orig_vs_para}).
To this end, we calculate the discourse motif features (\S\ref{subsubsec:motif_diff_dist}) for both upper and lower segments of the graphs corresponding to each pair of original and paraphrased documents in the three test sets ($\ast\text{-Para}_{\text{Pegasus}}$) of the \textsc{HC3} and \textsc{DeepfakeTextDetect} datasets. Here, the upper segment denotes the neighborhood graph of the root node within an edge distance of 3. Similarly, the lower segment encompasses the union of neighborhood graphs of individual EDU nodes within one edge distance. We average the motif features over the original and paraphrased documents and compute the absolute distance between the two groups.

\begin{figure}[!ht]

