\section{Introduction}\label{sec:introduction}

The emergence of powerful instruction-tuned large language models (LLMs) \citep{Ouyang2022Instruct,muennighoff-etal-2023-crosslingual, Kopf2023OpenAssistantC} has led to an explosion of machine-generated texts in both offline and online domains. Consequently, discerning the authorship of texts has become a significant challenge, spanning from educational settings to the landscape of online advertising \citep{Extance2023,DALALAH2023100822,GobAndrzejak2023}. Indeed, many efforts have been made in this direction by constructing corpora of machine-generated and human-authored texts \citep{dou-etal-2022-gpt,guo2023close,li2023deepfake} and developing models and benchmarks to tell them apart \citep{wu2023survey,verma2023ghostbuster,su-etal-2023-detectllm,chakraborty-etal-2023-counter}. The consensus seems to be that while classifiers that make use of the presence of LLM-specific signatures in the generated texts perform relatively well on in-domain texts, their accuracy drops significantly with out-of-domain samples. Furthermore, these detectors can be fooled easily with ``paraphrasing attacks'' even with in-domain samples \citep{sadasivan2023aigenerated,krishna2023paraphrasing}.
% motivation example: paraphrasing paper and publish!?

\begin{figure}[t!]
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{figures/concept_fig.pdf}
  \caption{Human writers often employ hierarchical linguistic structures in writing whereas LLMs primarily operate by the sequential next token prediction task.
  \vspace{-4mm}}
  \label{fig:conceptual_fig}
\end{figure}


This raises interesting questions on the underlying nature of human-written texts: ``Are there any discernible, unique properties within texts crafted by humans?'' and if so, ``Might these distinctive signatures manifest at levels beyond surface structure?'' Undeniably, how we write varies greatly depending on the domain and intent addressed by the texts. Consider, for instance, the distinction between academic writing and a casual response on a Reddit post.
%\textbf{\footnote{\url{https://www.reddit.com}} }
% In the former, much attention is devoted to the logical progression of arguments and the overall structural coherence of the paper. Conversely, in the latter scenario, we would focus less on text organization and tend to follow a more spontaneous and less structured thought process.
The former pays much more attention to the logical progression of arguments and overall structural coherence, while the latter is characterized by a more spontaneous and less structured thought process.


\begin{figure*}[!ht]
  % % trim={left bottom right top},clip
  \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/main_intro_fig.pdf}
  \caption{Difference in motif distribution of machine-generated and human-written texts for Yelp domain. Below are the top discourse motifs for each authorship and their corresponding discourse relations with examples.}
  \label{fig:main_intro_fig}
\end{figure*}

On the contrary, LLMs simply generate texts sequentially based on the next token prediction task where the most likely next token in a sequence is predicted given the context of preceding tokens, i.e., $P(x_{t} | x_{1}..x_{t-1})$. Figure \ref{fig:conceptual_fig} illustrates this structural difference in the writing processes of LLMs and humans. 
We note that LLMs may also internally capture these hierarchical structures to some degree as a by-product, especially in their self-attention matrices \citep{xiao-etal-2021-predicting,huber-carenini-2022-towards}.
However, we are interested in investigating if there are any distinctive hierarchical structures that will help distinguish their authorship.

To answer these inquiries systematically, we draw inspiration from discourse analysis in linguistics \citep{mann1987rhetorical}, which uncovers structures found within a sentence, between sentences, and among the paragraphs of a document. Specifically, Figure \ref{fig:main_intro_fig} highlights our main approach:
Given texts written by humans and LLMs, we construct a hierarchical parse tree for each document. Subsequently, we transform these trees into recursive hypergraphs, allowing us to perform network motif analysis of discourse relationships. The essence of our analysis lies in computing the difference in the distribution of network motifs between texts generated by machines and those crafted by humans, identifying distinctive discourse patterns within each authorship. 

% \begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
%     \item Human-authored texts within formal domains exhibit a higher prevalence of hyperedge relations, which connect lower representations to higher ones (e.g., phrases to sentences and sentences to paragraphs), compared to those in informal domains. This supports our hypothesis on the degree of structurality of writing styles for humans. [\citehere{}]
%     \item Binary classifiers for authorship detection show improved performance with the augmentation of motif distribution on both in-domain and out-of-domain scenarios, confirming the efficacy of these features. In addition, the motif-augmented classifiers are also more robust against paraphrasing attacks. [\citehere{}]
%     \item (tentative) In the case of creative writing, machine-generated stories tend to show a continuous progression of more sequential plots compared to human-written stories. [\citehere{}]
% \end{itemize}

We summarize our contributions as follows:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item We present empirical findings indicating that (i) the utilization of ``discourse motifs'' serves as a promising initial approach to explore linguistic signatures beyond the surface level of texts; (ii) both LLMs and humans generate distinct discourse patterns influenced by domains, with human-written texts displaying more ``evenly branched out'' discourse trees based on the formality of domains.
    \item To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to demonstrate that integrating hierarchical discourse-level features into the authorship detection task results in enhanced and more robust performance.
    \item Addressing a critical gap in existing research, where machine-generated texts typically fall within the range of 200 to 500 tokens (i.e., a few paragraphs), we construct a dataset specific to the creative writing domain. This dataset is a significant contribution, featuring stories with lengths of up to 8K tokens (approximately ten A4 pages), providing a more comprehensive perspective on longer-form machine-generated content.
\end{itemize}

