Figure \ref{fig:shortest_path_len} depicts the bar plots of ASPL of the two groups over five domains. \zae{re-interpret results.} We can observe that the story generation task (\textsc{WP}) produces texts with the longest ASPL for both groups. While the ASPL for the other four domains is relatively consistent for machine-written texts, human-written texts show another two levels of change in ASPL. Specifically, both news summarization (\textsc{xsum}) and argument writing tasks (\textsc{cmv}) produce ASPL of length 7, followed by review writing (\textsc{yelp}) and table description writing (\textsc{sci\_gen}). This finding shows that human writers are more versatile in arranging linguistic structures of discourse depending on the (nature of) domains.

